description:
An artificial system consists of 256 agents on a grid world. Each agent has an internal state (a vector of numbers) that updates based on what it observes in its local neighborhood. Agents move around, consume resources to maintain energy, and reproduce when they accumulate enough energy. Agents with zero energy are removed.

During this observation period:
- Population remained stable at 256 agents
- Resources were distributed normally across the grid
- Agents alternated between movement and consumption

Measured properties of agents' internal states:
- Internal state update rate: 1.636 (higher = more rapid internal changes)
- Prediction accuracy: 0.000140 mean squared error (lower = agents better at predicting their environment)
- Information integration: 0.0774 (how much information is lost when the agents' internal states are analyzed in parts rather than as a whole; higher means the processing is more unified)
- Integration under perturbation: 0.0777 (measured after randomly altering some inputs; increased relative to normal — perturbation makes processing MORE unified)
